Section2.Para:
From SEM images, we can also note that the average diameter was remained nearly constant with growth time up to 2 h; but slightly increased for longer growth times (see Fig. 7). Similar behavior has been already reported by Postel et al. [38], whereas Guo et al. [31] have noticed increasing diameters with growth time. In both cases as in this experiment, the length increase is higher than the diameter increase, because of the axial direction [0001] along the c-axis has a higher growth rate than the lateral directions [



                    $10\bar{1}0$
                  ] and [



                    $01\bar{1}0$
                  ].

This can be explained from crystallographic consideration: the alternating stacked planes of O2− and Zn2+ in the ZnO wurtzite structure generate a normal dipole moment with the spontaneous polarization along the c-axis. The crystalline structure can be seen as the stacking order of tetrahedron, made of oxygen with zinc at the centre (Fig. 10), by sharing elements (corner, edge, or face of the coordination polyhedron). The growth rates of the different crystal faces are mainly related to these elements present at the interface and their reactivity. A corner of the tetrahedron can bond with a maximum of three tetrahedrons whereas an atom on the edge of the tetrahedron can bond only two coordination polyhedrons against one if the atom belongs to the face of the tetrahedron. Thus, the elements at a corner of the tetrahedron present a higher reactivity than the elements present on the edge, the latter having a higher reactivity than elements on a face of the tetrahedron. Therefore, the elements present at the corner show the highest reactivity compared with the other positions on the tetrahedron. In the ZnO wurtzite structure, the lateral faces (



                    $10\bar{1}0$
                  ) and (



                    $01\bar{1}0$
                  ) have tetrahedron edges at their interfaces; the axial faces (



                    $000\bar{1}$
                  ) and (0001) have faces and corner tetrahedron, respectively. 

                      Fig. 10

                        Coordination polyhedron in crystalline structure of the ZnO hexagonal wurtzite structure

From the above considerations, it appears that the (0001) faces present a higher reactivity leading to a higher growth rate compared with (



                    $10\bar{1}0$
                  ), (



                    $01\bar{1}0$
                  ), and (



                    $000\bar{1}$
                  ) faces.
